comment_data.body:
Please use Python functions and doctests to make sure the functions actually do their work. Example:
```suggestion
import cython

def test_round_float(value: cython.float):
    """
    >>> test_round_float(3.14)
    3.0
    """
```

If you stick to Python syntax, you can then also rename the file to `.py` to let the test runner execute it twice, once compiled, once in Python. That makes sure that both give the same results.

This is the kind of test that I wanted to see added to assure we don't break `round(x, n)` this way.
```suggestion
    return int(round_long_double(value))


def test_float_ndigits(value: cython.float, ndigits: cython.int):
    """
    >>> test_float_ndigits(1.25, 0)
   1.0
    >>> test_float_ndigits(1.25, 1)
   1.2 
    >>> test_float_ndigits(1.25, 2)
    1.25
    >>> test_float_ndigits(1.25, 3)
    1.25
    """
    return round(value, ndigits)
```

comment_data.body: I'd rather not update existing code when it's not necessary to change it. It makes searching the history (git blame) more difficult. When making global formatting changes, it should be done in a single separate commit (not as part of a fix/feature PR) so that git can be instructed to ignore the whole commit at need.
